Description:

treatment:"There is no effective treatment for White Spot Disease, making prevention and management essential. Farmers should implement strict biosecurity measures to prevent the virus from entering their farms. Using specific pathogen-free (SPF) shrimp and disinfecting all equipment and water sources can significantly reduce the risk of infection.Maintaining stable water quality is crucial to preventing stress-induced outbreaks. Regular monitoring of water temperature, pH, salinity, and dissolved oxygen levels can help create a healthy environment that reduces shrimp susceptibility to infections. Sudden environmental changes should be avoided, as they can weaken shrimp immunity and increase the risk of WSD.Infected shrimp should be removed immediately to prevent the spread of the virus. Draining and disinfecting affected ponds before restocking is essential to eliminate any viral particles. Using probiotics and immune-boosting feed additives can help enhance shrimp resistance to infections.Some studies suggest that natural antiviral agents, such as seaweed extracts and immunostimulants, may help strengthen shrimp defenses against WSSV. However, these methods should be used as preventive measures rather than treatments. Regular health checks and early detection through PCR testing can help farmers take immediate action to minimize losses.",
